english:
  title: 'Inscription in Praise of the Royal Calligraphy: With Preface'
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Minister Tao of the National Academy spoke to me, saying: "My unworthiness you know well. My talents fall short of managing duties, my learning insufficient to answer questions. Yet I have received the sovereign's favor and been elevated to a position of honor near the throne. What debt could I repay, though I died ten thousand deaths? Recently, during the leisure hours of the royal lecture, His Majesty inscribed in large characters my name, courtesy name, and sobriquet—eight characters in all—as a gift. I received them with reverence, yet day and night I tremble with gratitude. How can such extraordinary grace fall upon me? I wish to have this framed and present it to scholars and officials, asking them to compose verses praising the sovereign's virtue, so that my humble name might be remembered through the ages. Will you not lead the way? You gave me the name Tao, you gave me the courtesy name Changwon, you inspired the sobriquet Naebok Hermit. I pray your kindness extends forever."

    Considering this royal gift, I have observed that when the sovereign bestows calligraphy upon his ministers, it contains either a name, or a courtesy name, or a sobriquet alone. Never before has one received all three so completely inscribed. Is it not fitting that Master Kim's joy exceeds all expectation? I shall explain the meaning behind the names given, revealing why he was so honored, establishing the foundation for praising the sovereign's virtue.

    When Master Kim first passed the civil examination, he brought me his compositions for revision. Reading them, I found a polished brilliance, the mark of a true writer. Within a month his prose had advanced further still. My delight was profound. When he requested a name, I gave him Tao, to honor his eloquence. When he requested a courtesy name, I bestowed Changwon, to warn him to remember his origins. Subsequently, he rose through the examinations, serving as Censor and Remonstrator, his talents increasing daily.

    When the new Emperor ascended and summoned scholars from across the realm to the examination at Jinling, Korean scholars shrank from crossing the sea. Master Kim alone laughed boldly, saying: "I merely test my abilities. Life and death are destiny—what is there to fear?" He traveled to the autumn examination, passed the metropolitan test, and presented his strategy before the throne, ranking among the highest—twenty-fifth of one hundred twenty successful candidates. His superiority is evident.

    When appointed magistrate, he requested leave to care for his aging parents. The sovereign approved, saying: "Able indeed." Thus he received extraordinary favor. This complete inscription represents the sovereign's recognition of Master Kim's exceptional talents and learning.

    As for the sobriquet Naebok Hermit, there are three explanations. The Kim clan originated from Yeomju; Dongbok is his maternal home, known by the name Naebok. His parents dwelt there—his birthplace. Moreover, the naebok plant, though common, is neither despised nor prized. It benefits humanity without harm. A person embodying such virtues would navigate this world with ease.

    Master Kim's features resembled those of Seol Cheonmin. An official once greeted him asking after Cheonmin, and Kim answered obliquely before departing. Listeners laughed at this wit. The Seol clan descends from the Khitans; thus his friends called him "Khitan." The Khitans are pure in character, temperate in appetite, and waste nothing—even the remnants of the naebok root.

    The sovereign once said: "Kim Tao resembles Seol Chopchai"—Cheonmin's uncle. Thus the sobriquet Naebok Hermit arose not from my intention alone.

    These eight characters—Kim Tao, Changwon, Naebok Hermit—inscribed by the sovereign's hand, represent a rare celestial honor. What minister would not strive to fulfill the sovereign's noble purpose?

    *Inscription in Praise:*

    In this time of perfect peace, the sovereign's heart finds rest.
    To encourage his servants' talents, grace is dispensed.
    Frost spreads its white; luminous dew glistens with sheen.
    Where the brush turns, jade and gold ring out clear.
    The heavens shine with stars; spirits weep in the shadows.
    Sublime perfection achieved—words cannot capture its form.

    The sovereign's virtue flows like wind:
    All it touches awakens with sound.
    Whoever remains deaf to this becomes bestial.
    Yet those in office—hear these words well!
  footnotes:
    - 'The eight characters refer to the full formal designation: family name (Kim), personal name (Tao), courtesy name (Changwon), and sobriquet (Naebok Hermit).'
    - Naebok (蘿葍) refers to a humble plant, symbolizing unpretentious virtue and contentment—virtues Lee Saek attributes to Master Kim.
    - Seol Cheonmin and Seol Chopchai were historical figures; the comparison suggests both physical resemblance and moral qualities.
    - The metropolitan examination (會試) was the second-stage imperial civil service examination; passing it and ranking 25th among 120 was exceptional achievement.
